{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659212"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:03:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:03:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20856"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20856"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.25,0.65,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13731"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96465"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13731"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20856"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79107"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12333"},{"type":"tags","id":"12338"},{"type":"tags","id":"12675"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33051"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96465"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the oncogenic mechanism of HTLV-1?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct inhibition of tumour suppressor proteins","Consistent integration near specific proto-oncogenes","Insertion of viral oncogenes into host genome","Expression of viral Tax and HBZ proteins that alter host cell function","Induction of chromosomal translocations"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe oncogenic mechanism of HTLV-1 primarily involves the \u003Cstrong\u003Eexpression of viral Tax and HBZ proteins that alter host cell function\u003C/strong\u003E. Unlike some other retroviruses, HTLV-1 does not contain a viral oncogene or consistently integrate near specific proto-oncogenes. Instead, the Tax and HBZ genes encode proteins that alter host cell gene transcription and interact with cellular signaling pathways, contributing to the acquisition of cancer hallmarks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsertion of viral oncogenes into host genome\u003C/strong\u003E - HTLV-1 does not contain viral oncogenes, unlike some animal retroviruses.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConsistent integration near specific proto-oncogenes\u003C/strong\u003E - No consistent integration site next to proto-oncogenes has been discovered for HTLV-1. The integration sites are random across different cancers, though clonal within a single cancer.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect inhibition of tumour suppressor proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - While Tax and HBZ may indirectly affect tumour suppressor pathways, direct inhibition of tumour suppressor proteins is not the primary mechanism.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduction of chromosomal translocations\u003C/strong\u003E - HTLV-1 is not known to directly cause specific chromosomal translocations as its primary oncogenic mechanism.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clonal integration pattern of HTLV-1 in leukemic cells indicates that the virus was present at the time of cellular transformation. The Tax and HBZ proteins contribute to oncogenesis through multiple mechanisms, including alteration of intracellular signaling, induction of genomic instability, and inhibition of cellular senescence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Human T-cell leukemia virus type 1 (HTLV-1) is the only human retrovirus firmly implicated in causing cancer, specifically adult T-cell leukemia/lymphoma.","HTLV-1 has tropism for CD4+ T cells and is transmitted via sexual intercourse, blood products, or breastfeeding.","The viral Tax and HBZ genes play key roles in HTLV-1\u0027s oncogenic potential by altering host cell gene transcription and signaling pathways."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; page 324."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79107"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20856"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79107"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T17:13:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T17:15:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13731"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96465"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neoplasia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":6,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12333"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Carcinogenic agents and th